hopobject.name: Page
hopobject.body: It's a bad line primemed.co.nz People with autism may be as good or better at a particular job than someone who is not on the spectrum, says Lisa Goring, vice president of family services at Autism Speaks, though they will likely need special accommodations to be able to work to their potential. Some mainstream businesses such as Walgreens are known for accommodating people on the spectrum, but there aren't nearly enough opportunities, Goring says. So parents are increasingly filling the void.
